steps.description:
In order to achieve proper drainage and prevent a collapsed or heaved driveway, the surface should be graded so that water runs off to the sides or bottom. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e4/Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e4/Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Run a hose at the top of your driveway to determine where the water runs. Keep in mind that this sub-base must be completely dry before putting in new asphalt so that the asphalt will adhere fully when installed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Build mounds and fill in low spots to achieve the proper grade. An optimal slope is 1/4 inch per foot (0.635 cm per 30.48 cm). {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/28/Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/28/Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Install-Asphalt-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The type of crushed rock used is crucial to proper drainage. The composition of the rock should be coarse and jagged. This type is usually called '3/4" minus' or 'Road-base' mix. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5c/Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5c/Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If your underlying soil is clay-based, you will need 8 inches (20.32) of crushed rock. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/08/Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/08/Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If your underlying soil is sandy, you will need 4 inches (10.16 cm) of crushed rock. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Install-Asphalt-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
